    "Description": "Primary and foreign key constraints are fundamental mechanisms for enforcing referential integrity within a relational database, ensuring that relationships between tables remain consistent. However, defining these constraints alone does not automatically create the necessary indexes on the referencing (foreign key) columns. Manually creating non-clustered indexes on these foreign key columns is a critical performance optimization; it significantly speeds up JOIN operations and improves query execution time by allowing SQL Server to quickly locate related records during lookups and constraint validation checks.",
